english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Master Muxuan
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, does the rise and fall of literary arts not respond to the breath of heaven and earth?

    When the Yuan's founding emperor unified all lands beneath heaven, scholars of letters gathered like spokes before the imperial gates. Master Muxuan, following King Chungson into audience with the emperor, found the sovereign seated at ease without his crown. Suddenly the emperor declared: "Though you are a prince, you are my grandson by marriage; though he is merely an attendant, he is a man of learning. How can I receive a scholar of the Way without proper ceremony?" Thereupon the emperor dressed himself in full regalia and sat with dignity. He then asked: "What strategy shall we employ to pacify Annam?" The Master, kneeling, replied: "To exhaust our armies in distant campaigns cannot match sending emissaries to call them forth in peace."

    Such was the learning of Master Muxuan. Thus when his brush gave forth its words, they captured the depths of human sentiment and the myriad forms of nature with perfect grace, flowing like water without resistance. Scholars have honored him as their guide to this very day.

    His great-grandson, an official of the Bureau of Literature, having received his great-uncle's request, came to seek a preface from me. I accepted and began to read. Though I have not yet finished, the purity of these works gleams like gold and jade newly released from rough stone, while their brilliance darts like fish in streams and birds amid clouds. In his memorials to the throne and official histories he refined, in the frameworks and structures he established—truly, he stands alone in his age.

    I was born late, yet I have been fortunate to walk among his descendants and hear the remaining echoes of their literary and moral legacy. How much more then should they, with their devotion to our Way, treasure the remembrance of their ancestor's brilliance? To know this beauty yet fail to transmit it would be a failure of duty. Thus their urgent request for this preface, that they might commit it to the woodblocks, comes as no surprise.

    Our Eastern lands have gained renown for literary achievement—a fame that began, I believe, with Choi Munchangk. Now many scholars answer the imperial examination. Yet most merely read examination papers from without, never seeing the throne room face to face. Master Muxuan alone entered the inner chambers to judge the great affairs of empire—an achievement no mere examination scholar could reach, surpassing even the great ministers of old. I had long wished to sing his deeds for posterity, but never completed the task. Now that his descendants have sought my words, I do so gladly, though my brush is crude and unequal to the subject.

    By opening with the rise and fall of letters, I honor the Master. Yet in doing so, I cannot help but sigh for my own age as well.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Master Muxuan (黙軒) is the pen name of the earlier sage being commemorated in this preface, honored for both his learning and his principled conduct before the Yuan emperor.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to receiving a scholar without proper crown reflects the Confucian principle that ceremony and respect form the foundation of proper governance.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Saek, the author, positions himself as one born too late to know Master Muxuan directly, yet finds meaning in preserving his memory through the written word.
